Description. A rather large, moderately stout species. Fastigium verticis (
Fig. 7 E
) broader than scapus, or exceptionally only as broad as scapus, shallowly furrowed above. Postfemora with 4–13 spinules on interior and exterior ventral margins.

Male. Pronotum (
Fig. 7 A–D
) moderately to distinctly raised in metazona (in a few males bred in laboratory ex ovo strongly raised), lateral margins slightly diverging in metazona; apex faintly concave to almost truncate. Tegmina usually covered by pronotum for circa half of their length. Stridulatory file (
Fig. 9
A) with 187–241 stridulatory teeth (
Tab. 6
), of which 110–160 are narrow. Cerci (
Fig. 7 F–G
) curved in apical quarter but less strongly than in the following species, gradually narrowing into apical tooth. Subgenital plate with lateral margins converging in apical half, with a median keel in apical half distinct or only indicated; apex truncate to faintly excised.

Female. Pronotum faintly raised in metazona; apex truncate. Tegmina overlapping, largely hidden under pronotum; protruding part rounded. Cerci slightly curved, apex subacute. Subgenital plate small with a weak median keel; apex rounded to almost triangular, with or without a small median emargination. Ovipositor (
Fig. 7 H
) long, apex dentate.
